JAPANESE ENCEPHALITIS - CHINA (HONG KONG)
******************************************

A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sat 6 Aug 2011
Source: RTHK [edited]
http://www.rthk.org.hk/rthk/news/englishnews/news.htm?englishnews&20110806&56&775126


Hong Kong has confirmed its 1st case of Japanese encephalitis in 4
years.

The patient, a 6-year-old girl, was admitted to Tuen Mun hospital with
fever and vomiting last month [July 2011]. She is now in stable
condition. She had no recent travel history, and 4 of her family
members are under medical surveillance.

Japanese encephalitis is a mosquito-borne viral disease.

--
Communicated by:
Health Map Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Hong Kong is well within the geographic distribution of JE virus.
ProMED-mail archive no. 20040623.1672 indicated that from 1992 to
2003, there have been 7 sporadic cases of JE reported in Hong Kong,
including one local case in 1996, one imported case in 1997, one
imported case in 2001, 2 imported cases in 2002, and one local case in
2003 and 2004.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map showing the location of Hong
Kong can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/0nTt. - Mod.TY]
